It's one of those things that you only seem to catch the first time reading, for after several reads you already have the scene in your head and you rely more on memory that the actual interpretation of the words to imagine the scene. Basically each sentece here could be helped with complimentary details. Readers don't always rely soley on the the words like a punch card reader. Rather they are always associating every word or phrase with a memory or idea, even if what your writing down doesn't make sense, the brain will subconsciously try to make sense of it, filling in details where there are holes. You can direct or lead this process. Guide them where they should be thinking. Is the guy a priest? If so you can hint or lead torward that idea of pioty and religion before you even directly address him: "Father MacDonald" in ways such as

Father MacDonald reached down and set the pyre alight, sending brother Finn's soul free of his earthly remains.
>what is he wearing? --> Could Denote religious ware?
>what are his surroundings? --> formal ceremony? Is it in secret? Is he surrounded by people or a person like him, denoting a clan or brother hood of sorts.
>mood of it all --> somber, foggy dewy morning?
>how big is the pyre? --> What time of year?

Zootopia is set on Mars several thousand years into the future. Massive biological engineering for the purpose of rapid terraforming (hundreds of years instead of hundreds of thousands) and other less than official goals was undertaken. This also resulted in many species of mammal undergoing the process known as uplifting. Long before the whole project could come to fruition, however, a war between Earth and Mars broke out. Due to Earth having vastly more difficulty reaching Mars than vice versa, Earth simply starved Mars of the resources it was still reliant on Earth for. Mars, on the other hand, simply dropped rocks on Earth in a volley of supermassive kinetic batteries. To avoid total annihilation, the Martians had no choice but to turn to cryogenics and hope that they would eventually awaken to a terraformed Mars, ready for a completely self-sufficient human presence. Those at the top knew of the experiments to uplift many animals. Because of this, they decided to build an enormous cryostasis vault on Phobos which would periodically emit a message over radio. This was to avoid them being brought out of cryostasis too early by the now natives, but to also ensure that they would not go undiscovered and thus left in cryostasis. Finally, after a couple thousand years, Mars has not only been successfully terraformed by the previous efforts, but has also come to harbor intelligent life of its own. These many different species, all with the same upbringing they knew nothing of, have advanced through the ages. Since the earliest days of their discovery of radio they have heard something coming from the sky. For many years its source, reason, origin, and everything about it was the subject of heated speculation. Only now, nearly a hundred years after they first heard those messages, with the maturation of their space program, have they finally found the answer to one of the greatest questions that faced their entire civilization.
